Since the stated goal is to support the `&`, `|` and `^` operators for sets, the minimal addition is 3 methods:
```java
public static <T> Set<T> and(Set<T> left, Iterable<T> right) { }
public static <T> Set<T>  or(Set<T> left, Iterable<T> right) { }
public static <T> Set<T> xor(Set<T> left, Iterable<T> right) { }
```

I'd suggest leaving everything else on the cutting room floor.  `SortedSet` implements `Set` and your extension implementation does not require the distinction, correct?  Update: Except that the `SortedSet` variant lets you keep the `SortedSet` semantic for the return type.

My other concern is that the operators are not commutative.  "set & iter" goes here and "iter & set" will be method missing.  I actually preferred the form of the first commit for this reason.

DGM is a bit unorganized at the moment, but it is best to keep overloads grouped, so new `and` methods should be added where `and` is declared or all `and`s should be moved as a group to somewhere appropriate.  Same for `or` and `xor`.  `ArrayGroovyMethods` demonstrates alphabetical ordering.

The changes to the plain `flatten` seem fine.  The changes to the closure variant I'm thinking about.  Should you say Array, Collection and Optional handled internally and all else goes to the closure?  If the closure can bear optionals, then you lose all guarantees of it returning `? extends T`.

```java
public static <T> Collection<T> flatten(Iterable<T> self, Closure<? extends T> flattenUsing) {
//                          ^^^                                  ^^^^^^^^^^^^^
```

